---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Callout from "~/components/Callout.astro";
---

<Section id="tradeoffs" num="12" title="What the server learns — honest trade-offs">
  <p>
    PIR is not magic. It hides specific things and leaves other things
    visible; pretending otherwise would be worse than not using PIR at all.
    Here's the shortlist for BitcoinPIR as it stands today, straight from
    the project's own notes.
  </p>

  <div class="grid-2" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <div class="backend-card" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--ok);">
      <h4 style="color: var(--ok);">Server CANNOT learn</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Which scripthash you queried</li>
        <li>Which specific PBC groups contain your real queries (padding hides this)</li>
        <li>Which bin inside a group you cared about (DPF/FHE keys are opaque)</li>
        <li>Whether a returned bin was tampered with (Merkle root binds the data)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="backend-card" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--warn);">
      <h4 style="color: var(--warn);">Server CAN observe</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Whether chunk / Merkle rounds ran.</strong> This reveals
          whether a query hit a UTXO (<em>found</em>) or not (<em>not&nbsp;found</em>).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Roughly how many chunk rounds.</strong> This gives a fuzzy
          lower bound on the queried address's UTXO count.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Timing patterns across rounds.</strong> Same client
          connection, repeatable cadence.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout label="A known, documented gap">
    <p>
      To hide found-vs-not-found completely, the client would have to run
      the optional CHUNK and MERKLE rounds even when the INDEX result was
      empty. That's cheap enough to be worth doing for privacy-critical
      wallets but costs bandwidth; it's a standing trade-off the project
      calls out explicitly in
      <code>CLAUDE.md</code> ("documented trade-off"). If you build on
      BitcoinPIR, make a conscious choice about whether to always issue the
      follow-up rounds.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Beyond the server</h3>
  <p>
    Everything above is about a single honest-but-curious server (or a pair
    of servers for DPF). There are adversaries PIR doesn't address on its
    own:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Network-level observers.</strong> TLS is assumed. PIR doesn't
      hide that you're a wallet talking to a PIR server — use Tor or a
      similar transport if that matters to your threat model.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Colluding servers</strong> (for DPF-PIR only). DPF assumes
      its two servers do not share keys or logs. If they do, the whole
      privacy argument collapses back to the naive case. OnionPIR and
      HarmonyPIR are single-server schemes and have no analogous
      assumption.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Compromised client state.</strong> PIR doesn't help if
      somebody reads your wallet's cache directly. For HarmonyPIR this is
      a bit sharper: the hint table is what keeps the random permutation
      private, so if it leaks, the server can in principle correlate past
      queries in the current epoch.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    PIR buys you a specific, narrow, useful property: the server cannot
    learn which address you're watching. Everything else in your wallet's
    threat model still applies.
  </p>

  <hr/>
  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted); font-size: 0.95rem;">
    That's the whole system. If you want to go deeper, the code is the
    canonical reference — start with
    <a href="https://github.com/BitcoinPIR/BitcoinPIR/blob/main/CLAUDE.md">CLAUDE.md</a>,
    then <a href="https://github.com/BitcoinPIR/BitcoinPIR/blob/main/pir-sdk-client/src/dpf.rs">pir-sdk-client/src/dpf.rs</a>
    for the full DPF query flow, and
    <a href="https://github.com/BitcoinPIR/BitcoinPIR/blob/main/pir-core/src/params.rs">pir-core/src/params.rs</a>
    for the constants that drive everything above.
  </p>
</Section>
